## Decisions

### D1: Hero variant — C' over D

C' ("AIDE collapses the specialist hire into the agent loop") is more concrete
and verb-first than D ("Give your agents a domain expert that stays with the
project"). C' also directly names the mechanism (collapse + agent loop) while
D is slightly more abstract ("stays with the project"). The spec allows
implementor choice; this plan recommends C' but the implementor may switch to D
if they disagree.

### D2: Brain visualization — inline callout, not sidebar

The spec requires single-column vertical layout. A true two-column layout
(pipeline left, brain right) would violate this. Instead, the brain should be
rendered as a visually distinct callout card within the single-column flow,
positioned after or alongside the pipeline nodes. The callout should use
connector annotations (e.g., "researcher writes / domain expert reads /
architect reads playbook") rather than actual drawn lines, keeping the
implementation in pure Tailwind without SVG or canvas.

### D3: VsRulesPacks ammunition selection — headline features first

The spec's ammunition-budget note is explicit: "six agents, Obsidian brain, and
auto-learning are the headline features. Misalignment tags, resume-mid-pipeline,
and upgrade are supporting mechanisms." The five bullets ship all three headline
features (agents via cascaded specs, brain as cross-project knowledge,
auto-learning) plus QA-checks-against-intent and coding playbook. Upgrade command
and misalignment tags are excluded as supporting — they belong in docs or beat 3
annotations, not headline LP copy.

### D4: Fix loop and resume-mid-pipeline — annotations, not beats

The spec says these mechanisms should be "visible as mechanism annotations, not
hidden." But it also says "not every new mechanism needs LP copy." These land as
brief annotations within the HowItWorks section — a one-liner on the QA node
for the fix loop, and a one-liner at the pipeline level for resume. They do not
get their own visual blocks or expand the section significantly.

### D5: Headline change is in scope

The delegation called out the subhead specifically, but the headline "Ship
intent, not instructions" is methodology framing that the spec explicitly says
belongs in beat 3, not the hero. The spec says "the hero leads with the business
outcome." Changing the headline is required for spec compliance even though the
delegation didn't name it explicitly. The spec is the contract.
